Gene Expression Data Analysis¶

@Author: wangyanli(wangyanli1@genomics.cn) \ @Created time: 2022.09.02

This is the answer notebook to the code test.

Requirements:

  • 降维
  • 聚类
  • (Advanced): 寻找每个类样本的特征基因并通过特征基因对该类样本进行注释

小结：

  • 原矩阵： 46,376 rows(samples) x 19,782 colums (genes)；过滤处理后：1305 × 11361
  • 通过PCA/UMAP对原基因表达矩阵进行降维，选择 10 PCs
  • 使用Leiden图算法对数据进行聚类，尝试分成 9 类，但差异性分析后特征基因有不同聚类间重叠，减少聚类数为 4 类
  • 根据特征基因对聚类进行标注

存在问题/改进方向（需要进一步验证或分析）：

  • 数据处理：如何定义“low-quality”的阈值；对线粒体基因的处理方式
  • 聚类：聚类数确定
  • 差异性分析：LR与Wilcoxon秩和检验两种算法结果的对比

1. Dimension Reduction¶

Here I choose UMAP to reduce the dimension of gene expression data.

UMAP (Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection) is a manifold learning technique, highly recommended by Scanpy, which is suitable for visualizing high-dimensional data:

  • compared with PCA, UMAP can expect non-linear relationships. In PCA, each PC contributes to explaining some proportion of total variance, while the UMAP1, UMAP2, or etc. don't have practical meaning.
  • compared with tSNE (another manifold learning method), UMAP runs faster and is less computing-tensive. UMAP updates the optimization way from gradient descent(GD) to stochastic gradient descent(SGD). In practice, the UMAP performance appears to linearly while tSNE scales exponationally.
  • compared with tSNE, UMAP could also maintain the global structure as well as the original topology.

Ref:

  1. https://scanpy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/generated/scanpy.tl.umap.html
  2. https://arxiv.org/pdf/1802.03426.pdf
  3. https://www.nature.com/articles/nbt.4314

2. Clustering¶

Leiden graph-clustering method is utilized, recommended by Scanpy.

Compared with Louvain algorithm, one of the most common algorithms for uncovering community structure, Leiden method updates the previous one to overcome the cases where some of the communities found by Louvain are badly connected. It is also proven that all subsets of all communities are locally optimally partitioned, in addition to a faster convergence rate.

Ref:

  1. https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.08473
In [28]:
sc.tl.leiden(adata, resolution=1, key_added="clusters") # resolution: default: 1; A parameter value controlling the coarseness of the clustering. Higher values lead to more clusters. 
sc.pl.umap(adata,color="clusters", title='clustering of cells')

Change resolution to "merge" the clusters. Since the subsequent analysis of genetic differences between clusters found that there were some overlaps between clusters, it was decided to lower this parameter.

In [119]:
# change resolution - fair performance
sc.tl.leiden(adata, resolution=.3, key_added="clusters") # resolution: default: 1; A parameter value controlling the coarseness of the clustering. Higher values lead to more clusters. 
sc.pl.umap(adata,color="clusters", title='clustering of cells (resolution=.3)')

3.3 Wilcoxon rank sum test¶

Recall the assumptions of the two-sample T-test, it requires the following assumptions:

  1. Two samples are independent of one another
  2. Two populations have equal variance
  3. Two populations are normally distributed

In this case, gene expression data among different "clusters" appear to conflict with assumptions 2 & 3 (should be further verified), while the Wilcoxon rank sum test could remedy this, namely, it only requires the first two assumptions: independence and equal variance. It does not assume populations possess a known distribution.

Ref:\ https://data.library.virginia.edu/the-wilcoxon-rank-sum-test/

In [92]:
# Scanpy recommending using Wilcoxon rank-sum (Mann-Whitney-U) test

sc.pl.rank_genes_groups(adata, n_genes=25, sharey=False)
